he warrior saint’s legendary exploits, then tracks the many ways he has been commemorated in the centuries since. The intriguing stories, ballads, and proverbs that grew up around Ghazi Miyan were, Amin shows, a way of domesticating the conquest—recognizing past conflicts and differences but nevertheless bringing diverse groups together into a community of devotees. What seems at first glance to be the story of one mythical figure becomes an allegory for the history of Hindu-Muslim relations over an astonishingly long period of time, and a timely contribution to current political and historical debates.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aUttar Pradesh (India) - Folklore. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  acommunity, afterlife, saint, historical figure, professor, academic, scholarly, textbook, university, research, analysis, classroom, educational, south asia, conquest, turkish, turks, indian, india, muslim, conqueror, communitarian, world history, international, legendary, soldier, conflict, political, folklore, cultural, sufi, ghazi, hagiography, urdu, hero, altars, warfare, birth, marriage, martyrdom, martyr, life story, biography, biographical.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107109840 cprintz978022637257040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226372747423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226372747/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles